<HTML> 
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Defining protection</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<P>
<P>
<P>
<TABLE>
<TR valign=top><TD>
<P><IMG SRC="/gifsICRC/IconICRC.gif" ALIGN=left HSPACE=10></TD><TD>
<P><IMG SRC="/gifsICRC/ButtonBar.gif" BORDER=0 USEMAP="#ButtonBar"><MAP NAME="ButtonBar"><AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="0,0,117,19" HREF="/index.htm"><AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="121,0,238,19" HREF="/icrcnews/neuf.htm" ALT="What's news"><AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="241,0,358,19" HREF="http://gvalnex1.icrc.org/icrcnews/search.htm" ALT="Search page"><AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="358,0,475,19" HREF="/icrcnews/SiteTree.htm" ALT="Site tree"></MAP><BR>

<P><B>1  April 1995</B>
<P>
<P><B>Extract from  &quot;Saving lives&quot;</B>  <B></B><BR>
</TD></TR></TABLE>

<P><IMG SRC="/gifsICRC/Separator_Line_ICRC.gif" BORDER=0><BR>

<P>
<P>
<H2>Defining protection</H2>
<P><I></I>
<P>
<P>In modern conflicts, most of the victims are civilians, although there are numerous provisions of international humanitarian law (IHL) intended to prevent this from happening. Faced with this reality the ICRC has developed the concept of &quot;protection&quot;, which encompasses the principles of IHL, to ensure the safety of all those who have no active part in the hostilities.<BR>

<P>Under the rules of IHL, civilians must be protected from two types of danger: First, that resulting from the fighting itself. Combatants are required to differentiate themselves clearly from civilians and to concentrate their attacks solely on military targets. Strategies that harm civilians (e.g. depriving them of water and food, bombardment or using them as human shields) are strictly prohibited.<BR>

<P>Secondly, the danger that arises when a territory populated by civilians is occupied by a foreign army or, for example, as in Bosnia-Herzegovina, when a minority group is of the same nationality as the enemy forces. In such cases the authorities are obliged to guarantee the safety of the entire civilian population and to see that basic rights are enjoyed by all civilians.<BR>

<P>
<H3><B>Dangers resulting from the conduct of hostilities</B></H3>
<P>
<P>In Bosnia-Herzegovina fighting often takes place near to - if not in the middle of - a town. Little or no respect is shown for civilians who might be trapped by gunfire and shelling. Many Bosnian cities have come under artillery fire aimed largely at non-military buildings and installations. The infamous &quot;sniper alley&quot; in Sarajevo is the most flagrant example of how combatants make no effort to spare civilians, with snipers making a game of using them as targets. Hospitals, which are afforded special protection in times of conflict, fare no better: many have been the target of artillery fire. <BR>

<P>Combatants justify their behaviour by claiming that the adverse side is using the building for military purposes. As a result, doctors and other medical staff who are often already working without electricity and water are not even able to give essential care to the wounded under proper security conditions.<BR>

<P>
<P><IMG src="3d52_0.gif"> Bistrovic/ICRC<BR>

<P>
<P>From the very beginning of the hostilities, civilians have been used as pawns by the parties to the conflict. They have been exploited ruthlessly for nationalist propaganda purposes and as a claim to legitimacy. Armed groups have prevented the entire population from leaving an exposed area, so as not to be seen defending a region without inhabitants, or have forced civilians to withdraw with them under difficult conditions. For example, some 30,000 civilians left the Bihac pocket in August 1994 and found themselves stranded in Turanj and Batnoga in no-man's-land. For several months as the harsh winter set in they were forced to shelter in the ruins of villages or in farm outbuildings, while the warring parties prevented any transfer to somewhere more hospitable where they could be supplied with basic necessities.<BR>

<P>With similar disregard for IHL and the welfare of civilians, combatants in Bosnia-Herzegovina have cut off supplies of drinking water, electricity, food and medicines for people on the opposing side as part of their strategy. Very often a population group is stranded in pockets such as Bihac, Gorazde, Vitez, Sarajevo or Srebrenica, its supply of drinking water, electricity, food and medicines totally dependent on the whim of the enemy forces. As long as the conflict around the pocket is of low intensity, some essential goods are allowed into the area; but as soon as fighting flares up, the surrounding forces block convoys of humanitarian aid intended to meet the most basic needs of the besieged population. Such an embargo on humanitarian supplies can last for several months, until a cease-fire agreement is reached. In Sarajevo, the warring parties bargain over the opening of UN &quot;blue roads&quot; by which humanitarian convoys and civilians can travel in and out of the city.<BR>

<P>
<H3><B>ICRC's response to the dangers resulting from the conduct of hostilities</B></H3>
<P>
<P>
<H4><B>Steps taken</B></H4>
<P>
<P>In addition to providing medical supplies and emergency food assistance since the outbreak of the conflict, the ICRC has remained in constant contact with the authorities on all sides and at all levels in an effort to induce them to spare civilian lives and property.<BR>

<P>The first step taken by the ICRC in May 1992 was to bring together the warring parties in Geneva with a view to having them sign an agreement, whose terms are set out on page 8 of this brochure. On the basis of this agreement, delegates in the field have repeatedly called on the authorities to put an end to the most flagrant violations of IHL.<BR>

<P>
<H4><B>Presence in the field</B></H4>
<P>
<P>The ICRC's first aim is always to reach the victims and to deploy a sufficient number of people to gain a clear picture of developments as they occur. In Bosnia-Herzegovina, as in most conflicts, the parties do their best to influence the media by staging a propaganda campaign. On-the-spot presence and direct contact with the victims enable the ICRC to monitor the situation in an impartial manner and report on it independently and confidentially to the highest authorities. Thus its presence has a deterrent effect; this is one of the reasons why it is often so difficult for the ICRC to reach the victims, and why access remains its top priority.<BR>

<P>
<H4><B>Dissemination of the principles of humanitarian law</B></H4>
<P>
<P>One of the ICRC's main tasks is to make combatants aware of the humanitarian rules of conduct in order to limit suffering among civilians. To this end, delegates make extensive use of means of communication such as seminars for members of the armed forces, interviews in the media, television and radio spots, and leaflets distributed to soldiers on every possible occasion.<BR>

<P>
<P><IMG src="3d52_1.gif"> Barry/ICRC<BR>
<I>Distribution of food parcels: all media can be a means of disseminating IHL.</I><BR>

<P>
<H4><B>Protected zones</B></H4>
<P>
<P>Faced from the start of the hostilities in Bosnia-Herzegovina with the pernicious practice of &quot;ethnic cleansing&quot;, the ICRC has done its utmost to protect Croat, Muslim and Serb minorities in their places of residence, as well as displaced people, including former detainees, the wounded and reunited families. In late 1992 the ICRC proposed that protected zones be set up in accordance with the rules of IHL. To safeguard these areas the obvious choice was an international force provided by the United Nations.<BR>

<P>At the time the ICRC's proposal was not accepted by the international mediators or governments, but in April 1993 the Security Council adopted the concept of &quot;safe areas&quot;, first for Srebrenica then for Sarajevo, Tuzla, Zepa, Gorazde and Bihac. However the lack of a precise definition of these &quot;safe areas&quot;, and of the role of the peace-keeping forces has resulted in confusion and disillusionment.<BR>

<P>
<H3><B>Dangers facing minority groups</B></H3>
<P>
<P>One particular characteristic of the conflict in Bosnia-Herzegovina has been the efforts of the more radical factions to divide the republic into homogeneous Croat, Muslim and Serb communities. Owing to the mingling of these communities throughout the country, minority groups often find themselves in territory under the control of the opposing party.<BR>

<P>Personal animosities, war-induced hatred, propaganda and political affiliations often lead to violent attacks on minority groups sometimes with the collusion of the authorities. In addition to acts of violence and threats directed against individuals, religious and historical monuments have been blown up to eliminate undesirable evidence of minority cultures in a particular region.<BR>

<P><IMG src="3d52_2.gif"> Barry/ICRC<BR>

<P>
<P>Even when minorities are not subjected to such acts, they are treated as second-class citizens and are deprived by the authorities of the rights and protection afforded to others living in the same area. Jobless, they often remain confined to their homes for fear of being conscripted to work on the front lines or forced to perform unpaid labour. These people see no future in remaining in the region, and so they choose to go into exile.<BR>

<P>Not that this is an easy option. In addition to the emotional trauma of leaving one's home, would-be exiles face a number of practical obstacles: the costly exit visa demanded by the authorities; the extortionate price of a bus ticket charged by companies enriching themselves by transporting people to the border; and finally, on departure, the obligation to sign a declaration surrendering ownership of all property in the region.<BR>

<P>In certain areas the entire population has to work as a contribution to the war effort. Although this obligation should be the same for all civilians, it is clearly used as another means of discriminating against and humiliating minority groups. They are brought forcibly to the front lines where they have to dig trenches and perform other tasks to help the military, often at the cost of their own lives. In other cases minority groups refuse to fight against their own people and thus are imprisoned as military objectors. This kind of pressure is another contributing factor in driving minorities into exile.<BR>

<P>
<H3><B>ICRC's response to the dangers facing minority groups </B></H3>
<P>
<P>
<H4><B>&quot;Ethnic cleansing&quot; and IHL</B></H4>
<P>
<P>Humanitarian law is not against the movement of the civilian population as such, but rather the methods used to goad &quot;undesirables&quot; into leaving. In spite of the 1992 agreement whereby the three parties undertook to give civilians safe conduct to the destination of their choice, population movements always take place under duress.<BR>

<P>The ICRC must nonetheless refrain from taking sides by arranging the departure of these people, lest it appear to condone the practice of &quot;ethnic cleansing&quot; and the possession of territory by a party that has seized it by force. This dividing up of land and its inhabitants is a highly political issue which is outside the ICRC's mandate. The institution's role continues to be to remind the belligerents constantly of their obligations and to urge them to respect, and ensure respect for, the civilian population.<BR>

<P>
<H4><B>Presence in the field</B></H4>
<P>
<P>The ICRC has concentrated its efforts on bringing an end to the pressure exerted on minorities in order to drive them from their homes. It has requested the authorities to ensure the safety of minorities and thus allow them to continue to live in their customary places of residence. The agreement signed by the three parties on 22 May 1992, which pledged respect for all civilians, constitutes the working basis for the ICRC in this regard. Delegates have established a permanent presence throughout Bosnia-Herzegovina, and on several occasions, the ICRC has been practically the only international organization present in certain areas.<BR>

<P>
<H4><B>Evacuations</B></H4>
<P>
<P>The ICRC has decided not to encourage the departure of minorities. Nevertheless, in certain cases it has had to take action to ensure that at least people are transferred under decent and safe conditions. In summer 1994 when, despite the efforts made by the ICRC, 6,000 people were expelled from the Bijeljina area and transferred across the front lines, delegates could do nothing more than ensure that those involved would be accepted on the other side. Between June 1993 and March 1994 delegates had no option but to take part in the transfer from the Banja Luka region of some 1,000 people whose personal safety or lives were at risk.<BR>

<P>
<P><IMG src="3d52_3.gif">Cugini/ICRC<BR>
<I>A family together again, but in exile</I>.<BR>

<P>In April 1994 about 20 civilian members of a minority group in Prijedor were killed in retaliation for the killing of soldiers on the front line. The ICRC informed the authorities that it was willing to organize the evacuation of 6,000 members of this minority group from the city, since the authorities had been unable to guarantee their safety. Subsequently, extra police were deployed and the minority population received adequate protection.<BR>

<P><A HREF="2996.htm">Next page</A><BR>
