<HTML> 
<HEAD>
<TITLE> The ICRC's mandate in Bosnia-Herzegovina</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<P>
<P>
<P>
<TABLE>
<TR valign=top><TD>
<P><IMG SRC="/gifsICRC/IconICRC.gif" ALIGN=left HSPACE=10></TD><TD>
<P><IMG SRC="/gifsICRC/ButtonBar.gif" BORDER=0 USEMAP="#ButtonBar"><MAP NAME="ButtonBar"><AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="0,0,117,19" HREF="/index.htm"><AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="121,0,238,19" HREF="/icrcnews/neuf.htm" ALT="What's news"><AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="241,0,358,19" HREF="http://gvalnex1.icrc.org/icrcnews/search.htm" ALT="Search page"><AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="358,0,475,19" HREF="/icrcnews/SiteTree.htm" ALT="Site tree"></MAP><BR>

<P><B>1  April 1995</B>
<P>
<P><B>Extract from  &quot;Saving Lives&quot;</B>  <B></B><BR>
</TD></TR></TABLE>

<P><IMG SRC="/gifsICRC/Separator_Line_ICRC.gif" BORDER=0><BR>

<P>
<P>
<H2>The ICRC's mandate in Bosnia-Herzegovina</H2>
<P><I></I>
<P>
<P>The conflicts and tragedies that resulted from the break-up of the former Yugoslavia meant that the ICRC once again had to strive for the application of IHL, urging the parties to the conflict to provide better protection for those not or no longer directly involved in the hostilities. A number of rules need to be respected to preserve a minimum of humanity.<BR>

<P>
<H4><B>The protection mandate</B></H4>
<P>
<P>The States party to the Geneva Conventions have entrusted the ICRC with a humanitarian mandate to take action in times of armed conflict and to offer its services as a neutral and independent intermediary. Moreover the international community has given the ICRC a mandate to promote IHL and a right of humanitarian initiative to ensure that protection and assistance are provided in situations of internal violence, as the need arises.<BR>

<P><IMG src="2996_0.gif">
<P>
<P>
<H4>The 1992 agreements</H4>
<P>
<P>To be in a position to perform these basic tasks, in 1992 the ICRC took the initiative of convening meetings in Geneva with the various parties involved in the conflict in Bosnia-Herzegovina. All concerned stated their readiness to respect and apply IHL irrespective of the status of the conflict in legal terms and to instruct their combatants accordingly. The four agreements signed that year provide a useful point of reference between the parties to the conflict, and are regularly adapted to meet current requirements. Their main features are outlined here.<BR>

<P>
<H4>Agreement of 22 May<BR>
</H4>
<P>This simply referred to the provisions of the First, Second and Third Geneva Conventions relating to the treatment of the wounded and sick, the shipwrecked, and prisoners of war respectively. It stated that civilians, particularly those deprived of their freedom in connection with the conflict, would be treated humanely, in accordance with the Fourth Geneva Convention.<BR>

<P>The agreement also stipulated that hostilities have to be conducted according to IHL, especially the customary rules set forth in Protocol I additional to the Geneva Conventions. These specify that the civilian population must be protected against dangers arising from military operations, that civilian property must not be the object of attack or reprisals, and that civilians in need are entitled to receive assistance.<BR>
<BR>

<H4>Agreements of 23 May and 6 June<B><BR>
</B></H4>
<P>These pertained respectively to the setting up of a commission of liaison officers and to the restoration of the security conditions necessary for the ICRC to resume its activities.<BR>

<P>
<P><IMG src="2996_1.gif">
<P>
<P>
<H4>Agreement of 1 October<BR>
</H4>
<P>This provided for the release and transfer of all detainees other than those accused of serious violations of IHL. The conditions for such transfers were set out in detail, including the possibility of transferring detainees to neighbouring countries in cooperation with the office of the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR). Finally, the parties agreed not to recruit into their armed forces prisoners released or transferred under the agreement.<BR>

<P>
<H4><B>The principles of neutrality and independence</B></H4>
<P>
<P>The ICRC endeavours to use all means at its disposal to discharge the mandate conferred on it by the 185 States party to the Geneva Conventions. These States have on many occasions reaffirmed their commitment to respect in all circumstances the ICRC's obligation to act in accordance with the Fundamental Principles of the Movement[1], in particular the principles of neutrality and independence. The ICRC has repeatedly impressed upon all parties to the conflict and all agencies involved in Bosnia-Herzegovina that humanitarian activities have to be kept absolutely separate from military operations.<BR>

<P><BR>
<IMG src="2996_2.gif"><BR>

<P>
<H4><B>The ICRC's approach to protection work</B></H4>
<P>
<P>In order to gain wider access to all the victims that it intends to help, the ICRC assures the autho-rities that whatever information delegates obtain in the course of their activities will be reported solely to the said authorities and will not be made public. Thanks to this &quot;pledge of confidentiality&quot; the ICRC can continue its work regardless of any kind of propaganda and counterpropa-ganda. However, whenever serious and repeated violations of IHL persist despite confidential approaches, the ICRC does resort to public statements. The purpose of denouncing violations is also, and perhaps primarily, to point out that belligerents are accountable to the international community for their acts, as States party to the Geneva Conventions have undertaken &quot;to respect and ensure respect&quot; for IHL &quot;in all circumstances&quot;.<BR>

<P><IMG src="2996_3.gif">
<P>
<P>
<P>Whenever delegates hear of alleged atrocities, they first contact the local military or civilian authorities personally or by means of a written report requesting that steps be taken to avoid a recurrence of the incident (e.g. police deployment or a public statement by the authorities). Should this measure fail, the ICRC delegation contacts the central authorities. In accordance with its doctrine the ICRC has itself issued public statements on many occasions during the conflict in Bosnia-Herzegovina. The two most noteworthy cases were on 23 August 1992, when the ICRC was denied access to detainees in the Manjaca and Omarska camps, and on 7 September 1994, when the belligerents ignored repeated appeals from the ICRC and continued to fight with total disregard for the security of civilians. On both occasions the ICRC President contacted ambassadors of the States party to the Geneva Conventions to remind them of their obligations.<BR>

<P>
<H4><B>Note</B></H4>
<P>
<P>1. See Statutes of the International Red Cross and Red  Crescent Movement.<BR>

<P><A HREF="2e4e.htm">Next page</A><BR>
<A HREF="3d52.htm">Previous page</A><BR>
