<HTML> 
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Detention and detainees</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<P>
<P>
<P>
<TABLE>
<TR valign=top><TD>
<P><IMG SRC="/gifsICRC/IconICRC.gif" ALIGN=left HSPACE=10></TD><TD>
<P><IMG SRC="/gifsICRC/ButtonBar.gif" BORDER=0 USEMAP="#ButtonBar"><MAP NAME="ButtonBar"><AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="0,0,117,19" HREF="/index.htm"><AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="121,0,238,19" HREF="/icrcnews/neuf.htm" ALT="What's news"><AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="241,0,358,19" HREF="http://gvalnex1.icrc.org/icrcnews/search.htm" ALT="Search page"><AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="358,0,475,19" HREF="/icrcnews/SiteTree.htm" ALT="Site tree"></MAP><BR>

<P><B>1  April 1995</B>
<P>
<P><B>Extract from  &quot;Saving lives&quot;</B>  <B></B><BR>
</TD></TR></TABLE>

<P><IMG SRC="/gifsICRC/Separator_Line_ICRC.gif" BORDER=0><BR>

<P>
<P>
<H2>Detention and detainees</H2>
<P><I></I>
<P>
<P>
<H4><B>Prisoners of war?</B></H4>
<P>
<P>ICRC delegates who visited the first detainees in mid-1992 soon realized that although some of them were combatants captured while bearing arms the majority were civilians, including adolescents, women and elderly people who could hardly have taken an active part in the fighting. The definition of detainees within the ICRC's purview was consequently extended to &quot;anyone detained as a result of the conflict&quot;. This was tantamount to saying anyone belonging to an ethnic minority.<BR>

<P>Strong suspicion of spying, possession of weapons, and other allegations made to justify detention of these civilians almost never lead to a formal charge followed by sentencing or acquittal. After many months, detainees are left with one hope: to be bargained for and then exchanged for detainees in the same situation on the other side. The exchange procedure often involves signing a paper whereby detainees renounce all their property, thus giving up any hope of returning to their homes. Moreover, in many instances people are cut off from their families who have not been included in the exchange. This shows the extent to which detention plays a role in &quot;ethnic cleansing&quot; in Bosnia-Herzegovina, and how it has served to rid areas of those who do not belong to the majority population.<BR>

<P>
<H4><B>Access by the ICRC</B></H4>
<P>
<P>Under the agreements signed in 1992 by the parties to the conflict and witnessed by the ICRC, delegates were to have free access to every place of detention and every detainee. In reality, however, local leaders who from the outset have acted with considerable independence from their central authorities placed major hurdles in the way of the ICRC's work. Delegates in the field have to engage in endless negotiations with intermediaries who impose one unacceptable condition after another for opening the doors to their detention centres. The main lever used against the ICRC involves the principle of reciprocity, whereby visits are not allowed on one side until detainees held by the opposite side have been visited.<BR>

<P>Access to detainees has been complicated from the outset, because of a lack of cooperation and good faith on the part of the authorities concerned. For instance, in July 1992 the ICRC was not allowed to visit prisoners in places such as Brcko, Keraterm and Omarska. In 1993 it took delegates several weeks to gain access to detainees held in the Mostar region or to those held after the fighting in Bihac at the end of 1994 and in early 1995. The parties did not want witnesses to their unacceptable practices, including the execution of prisoners, especially at the beginning of the war. Furthermore, they used detention as a means of exerting pressure on thousands of civilians whose only wish, if they survived their ordeal, was to leave the area for good.<BR>

<P>
<P><IMG src="2e4e_0.gif"> Feric/ICRC<BR>
<I>The detention place pictured appears to be well kept...</I><BR>
<I>This is not always the case.</I><BR>

<P>
<H4><B>Conditions of detention</B><BR>
</H4>
<P>Hardship suffered by detainees can be attributed to two basic factors: ill-treatment and poor conditions in places not intended to hold dozens or even hundreds of people. Detainees are often held in premises not designed for the purpose, such as sports halls, barns and grain silos. <BR>

<P>The ICRC's task is to see that the detaining authorities do their duty and obtain the resources necessary for the survival of detainees. This means providing food and water of adequate quality and in sufficient quantity, proper hygiene and sanitation and heating in the winter. In most cases, the ICRC helps to improve conditions by distributing items such as clothing, blankets, soap, detergent and stoves. ICRC sanitary engineers may install or repair a basic water supply and sewage system, while a doctor sees that the pharmacy receives adequate supplies of medicines. Although the ICRC generally refuses to distribute food, for fear that this may encourage the holding of prisoners, in certain extreme cases it has had to set this rule aside.<BR>

<P>The most important and most sensitive purpose of visits, however, is to prevent disappearances and make sure that the detainees are not ill-treated. When systematic and severe ill-treatment became widespread in Bosnia-Herzegovina the ICRC worked long and hard to put a stop to such practices. However, because new outbreaks might occur at any time, the principle of repeated visits is becoming increasingly important.<BR>

<P>
<H4><B>Forced labour on the front lines</B><BR>
</H4>
<P>Despite their signed commitment to desist, the belligerents continue to use detainees on the front lines for mine-clearance operations and to dig trenches in areas where they are directly exposed to enemy fire; as a result many have been killed. The ICRC has spoken out on numerous occasions against this practice, and has submitted reports on the matter to the highest authorities of all three parties to the conflict, but the practice still persists.<BR>

<P>
<H4><B>ICRC participation in the exchange of detainees</B></H4>
<P>
<P>From the start of the conflict, the warring parties were quick to establish exchange commissions which drew up lists of all detainees available for barter with the other side. When the lists were complete, the commissions met to negotiate a formal exchange, which also involved mortal remains. Under this system, civilians were often arrested for the sole purpose of being exchanged should one party not have enough detainees to barter. Such people were frequently exchanged against their will, ending up separated from their families who were unable to cross the front line with them.<BR>

<P>The ICRC has always condemned the practice of exchanging detainees. However, it has had to accept the situation and takes action to ensure that the interests of detainees are taken into<BR>
account. In particular, it ascertains their wishes on their release, that is:<BR>
 	<BR>
<MENU><LI>		to remain in the area;</LI><LI> 		to be transferred under safe conditions to the other side of the front line;</LI><LI>		to be transferred to another country as a refugee.</LI></MENU><BR>

<P>The ICRC has occasionally managed to convince one side to release all the detainees it is holding in exchange for the release of all those held by the other side without taking specific numbers into consideration, rather than a one-for-one exchange. Nevertheless, the main purpose of the ICRC's work remains to visit the detainees, monitor their treatment and living conditions and keep track of them throughout their period of detention.<BR>

<P>
<P><IMG src="2e4e_1.gif">Sidler/ICRC<BR>
<I>Detainees are released under ICRC auspices</I><BR>

<P>
<H4><B>Manjaca camp, August-December 1992</B></H4>
<P><BR>
In 1992, during the first summer of the war in Bosnia-Herzegovina, shocking pictures appeared in the media: thousands of detainees were shown living in appalling conditions that spelled death for many of them. It took long weeks of negotiation before the ICRC was allowed access to the Manjaca camp. As soon as the delegates entered the camp they registered the detainees, so as to be able to check that they were still there during subsequent visits, set up a nutritional programme, and distributed basic necessities. Dozens of delegates were involved in this operation. Some 70 detainees suffering from severe health problems were evacuated on medical grounds to London on 15 September. The living conditions of the other 4,000 made it unlikely that they would survive the approaching winter, so the ICRC endeavoured to persuade the authorities to release them and empty the camp.<BR>

<P>The attitude of the three belligerent parties in Bosnia-Herzegovina was that no release was possible without a negotiated exchange of detainees, a principle which the ICRC had so far repudiated. The ICRC took the following step as a way out of this dilemma after the international conference on the former Yugoslavia held in London in August 1992: on 1 October the three parties, meeting with the ICRC, signed an agreement in Geneva whereby they undertook to release, unconditionally and unilaterally, all the detainees they were holding, regardless of their numbers, acknowledging that most of them were civilians.<BR>

<P>Some 5,600 detainees were released in that way between October and December 1992, accounting for half of the detainees registered by the ICRC in Bosnia-Herzegovina at the time. ICRC delegates interviewed each detainee in private to determine where he or she wished to go when released, and to arrange for transfer to another country if necessary.<BR>

<P>The Manjaca camp, along with several others, was completely emptied and closed on 18 December 1992. Earlier the Ternopolje camp, holding mainly women and children, had also been closed after ICRC delegates had monitored the return home or the transfer to Croatia of its inmates. Detainees leaving Bosnia-Herzegovina were turned over to UNHCR and the International Organization for Migration (IOM), which subsequently set up a programme whereby these detainees' families could join them in the host country.<BR>

<P>
<H4><B>The Mostar camps, May 1993-March 1994</B></H4>
<P>
<P>In May 1993, heavy fighting broke out between Bosnian Croat and Bosnian government forces (mostly Muslim) in the area around Mostar. Every male Muslim of an age to bear arms (some 6,000) was arrested and detained in one of three camps on Croat-held territory - Rodoc, Dretelj and Gabela - while some of their families were driven into government-held areas on the other side of the front line. The ICRC immediately requested access to all detainees, but this was not fully granted until August.<BR>

<P>The first challenge for delegates visiting the camps concerned the appalling living conditions. Some 500 detainees identified by the ICRC as suffering from severe malnutrition were transferred to the island of Korcula, outside Bosnia-Herzegovina, and placed in the care of UNHCR. Ill-treatment was brought to an end thanks to repeated ICRC visits to the remaining detainees, while food and other supplies were distributed to help make their living conditions bearable.<BR>

<P>In September, the Bosnian Croat and government authorities signed a bilateral agreement whereby all detainees they were holding were to be released; the ICRC placed itself at their disposal to ensure that this commitment was met. In the first phase of a large-scale ICRC plan, 770 Muslim and 310 Croat detainees were released on 19 October. Then the Croat authorities took the unilateral decision to close their camps and freed 2,500 detainees between 14 and 30 December. The remaining 1,500 prisoners held by both sides were released in March and April 1994, again under the auspices of the ICRC. This followed the signing in Washington of an agreement between the Bosnian Croat and Bosnian government authorities to establish a federation.<BR>

<P>
<H4><B>ICRC detention activities in Bosnia-Herzegovina</B></H4>
<P>
<P>
<TABLE border>
