<HTML> 
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Visiting a place of detention</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<P>
<P>
<P>
<TABLE>
<TR valign=top><TD>
<P><IMG SRC="/gifsICRC/IconICRC.gif" ALIGN=left HSPACE=10></TD><TD>
<P><IMG SRC="/gifsICRC/ButtonBar.gif" BORDER=0 USEMAP="#ButtonBar"><MAP NAME="ButtonBar"><AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="0,0,117,19" HREF="/index.htm"><AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="121,0,238,19" HREF="/icrcnews/neuf.htm" ALT="What's news"><AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="241,0,358,19" HREF="http://gvalnex1.icrc.org/icrcnews/search.htm" ALT="Search page"><AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="358,0,475,19" HREF="/icrcnews/SiteTree.htm" ALT="Site tree"></MAP><BR>

<P><B>1  April 1995</B>
<P>
<P><B>Extract from  &quot;Saving lives&quot;</B>  <B></B><BR>
</TD></TR></TABLE>

<P><IMG SRC="/gifsICRC/Separator_Line_ICRC.gif" BORDER=0><BR>

<P>
<P>
<H2>Visiting a place of detention</H2>
<P><I></I>
<P>
<P>The aim of ICRC delegates is to visit all detainees, and to ensure that their living conditions and the treatment they receive from guards are acceptable. In order to carry out the visit thoroughly, delegates have to do three things:<BR>
<BR>
		<I>- make sure that all detainees and all parts of the place of detention are seen;</I><BR>

<P><I>		- speak freely to all detainees in private, that is, without the presence of a guard;</I><BR>

<P><I>		- register every detainee in order to check that none are missing on subsequent visits.</I><BR>
	<BR>
The visit starts in the director's office. First the delegates explain the ICRC's mandate and the procedure for the visit. They then find out how the place of detention functions, consult the log book, etc. Often an ICRC doctor takes part in the visit to assess the detainees' general state of health.<BR>

<P>
<P><IMG src="367a_0.gif"> Feric/ICRC<BR>
<I>A name on a list is a proof of existance</I><BR>

<P>The second step involves contact with the detainees. With the help of an interpreter, the delegates explain briefly who they are, what they are doing and the advantages for detainees in being registered and in talking openly to the ICRC. Often the detainees are in a poor psychological state and are too frightened to trust foreigners who suddenly appear bearing a red cross: several visits will be necessary to establish a relationship of trust. While they talk to the detainees, the delegates learn what is really happening. They ask how the guards behave, about the quantity and quality of the food, whether medical treatment is provided, whether there is sufficient access to washing facilities and outdoor time, etc. They will also collect allegations concerning other persons detained who might be hidden, have disappeared or died. Finally comes the best moment for the detainees, when the lucky ones receive Red Cross messages from their families, and all can sit down and write their own messages to loved ones, and when they are handed a packet of cigarettes each.<BR>

<P>The information collected provides the basis for a final talk with the detaining authorities. At this stage complaints are passed on to the authorities and suggestions made. In the case of allegations of ill-treatment, an internal inquiry can be requested to put an end to it. If necessary, a written working paper is drawn up and handed over to the authorities concerned, then to higher authorities if no improvement is noted after several visits.<BR>

<P>In many cases the ICRC distributes material assistance in order to improve living conditions. This can consist of clothing, blankets, soap, books, games and medicine.<BR>

<P><A HREF="258a.htm">Next page</A><BR>
<A HREF="2e4e.htm">Previous page</A><BR>
<A HREF="3eba.htm">Table of contents</A></P><IMG SRC="/gifsICRC/Separator_Line_ICRC.gif" BORDER=0><P><IMG SRC="/gifsICRC/ButtonBar.gif" BORDER=0 USEMAP="#ButtonBar"><BR>

<P>
<P>
</BODY>
</HTML>
